A year ago, after several months of feeling the nudge to do so, I decided to log off of Instagram indefinitely. (See my stories for an explanation.). Over the last several months, I have felt good about coming back with different boundaries and resolves but have had a difficult time deciding what my new normal should look like. 
As my kids are now back in school and my work has resumed, I’ve finally decided to set aside  three or four days a week to share on Instagram.  These days will vary from week to week, but I plan to share my schedule each week on Sunday. 
Thankfully, at this time my family does not depend on my work on Instagram (or elsewhere) for support.  Therefore, I have the great luxury and blessing to work as much or as little as I choose. 
At the end of my life, I want people to say about me that I loved Jesus and tried hard to be like him, and that my highest priorities were trying to be the best wife and mother I could be. 
I want to make sure the way I spend my time aligns with those priorities.  Thank you for being here with me. ❤️❤️

This is such an easy, inexpensive  garland you can make and customize.  I used decorative cardstock here, but I’ve also used sheets of felt! (You could also use vinyl, fabric, etc!) I cut a bunch of 2” circles using a craft punch, but you can do it with scissors or use a Cricut, too.  After cutting out the circles (or other cute shape—the posibilítese are endless!), just feed them through your sewing machine, one after the other.  If you’re using one-sided paper, make sure to double up the circles (with the right sides showing.) At the end, don’t forget to do a couple backstitches!  That’s it!  If you’re using 2” circles, it will take 6 double circles to make a foot of garland—so 24 double circles to make a 6 ft. garland.  It goes super fast!  Enjoy!  Let me know if you’d like a link to this hole-puncher!

I was making this for a crowd, so I tripled this recipe: 

1 pound Italian sausage
1 clove garlic, minced
2 (14oz) cans beef broth
1 (14.5 oz ) can Italian-style stewed 
tomatoes 
1 cup sliced carrots
1 (14.5) oz can Great Northern beans, undrained
2 small zucchini, cubed
2 cups chopped fresh spinach 
1/4 t. salt
1/4 t. pepper

In a stockpot or Dutch oven, brown sausage with garlic and onions.  Stir in broth, tomatoes and carrots.  Reduce heat, cover, and simmer for 15 min. 

Stir in beans (with liquid) and zucchini. Season with salt and pepper. Cover and simmer another 15 min or until zucchini is tender.

Remove from heat and add spinach.  Stir in and serve! Garnish with grated Parmesan. Enjoy!

Dear Camp, 

Your absence is already keenly felt.  It’s weird because this isn’t the first time you’ve been gone.  But it feels different now.  I think more than anything else, I feel the loss of being the mother of your childhood.  Because you’re not a child anymore. 
On Monday, after your departure,  I felt a lonesome feeling tugging at me.  I walked over to a new house in the neighborhood—a house that has become home to two little girls!—and rang the bell.  I wanted to invite them (beg them?) to come trick or treating at our house.  But when they didn’t answer the door, I felt like bawling my eyes out.  I tried again later though, and this time, the mom said she’d talk to her husband to see if they could come by before heading out to Bay Street.  I promised that if they did, I’d have two goodie bags made up for them. (Remember when Marge used to do that for you kids?) And I kept my promise.  I was so delighted to see them coming up the walk about 3:30.  They were our only trick or treaters, so now I have a huge bowl of candy in my bottom drawer that I might repurpose for stocking stuffing. (Think it will last that long?) 
Over the last week, I’ve been able to help Jane and Dan with school stuff possibly more than in the last five years combined.  I spent a few late nights helping Dan study for her college world history exam (Alex stole a purse—>Alexander the Great conquered Persia) and helped Janey refine ALL SEVEN ESSAYS of her BYU application. (Really, BYU? Ha!) 
Skip has injured his left foot yet again after kicking a chair super hard during an aggressive game of chair soccer at Young Men’s.  Sigh.. 
Dad has starting taking walks at night.  I can’t decide if he’s having nightly phone conversations that he doesn’t want me listening in on, or if he’s just getting some exercise.  But I think it’s cool either way. 
Last night, after attending Les MIs at the Hult Center with Dan, I was whistling one of the songs while in the bathroom stall and the girl in the stall next to me started singing along. ❤️❤️It was a moment, I tell ya! 
I love you, Baby.  I can’t wait to hear every detail of your first week. 
Love, Mom

Well, I might not have started  decorating for the holidays yet, but I HAVE started decorating for the season.  I’ve switched out some of my toss pillows and brought in a lot of wool and plaid (it doesn’t get more cozy than that) aaaaand I just hung these new drapes from Pepper Home!  I actually like to keep my windows bare most of the year, but goodness!  What a different, more cozy feel they’ve given my living room! The perfect way to celebrate the season. ❤️ What do you think? 

#drapery #drapes #livingroominspiration #playfulpreppy

Tip 1:  Drapes should always hang all the way to the floor (or just baaaarely above it.) This means you will likely not be able to buy your panels off the shelves in a store because for some insane reason, stores usually only stock 84” drapes. 

Tip 2). The width of all your drapery panels together should be at least TWICE the width of your window.  My living room window is about 12 ft (148 inches) wide, so I got 300 inches worth of panels.  This means you will usually need at least two panels for each side of a window.  This ensures that when the drapes are closed, there will still be pleats or waves in them AND that when they are open, they are really full!  Believe me—following this tip makes ALL the difference! 

Tip 3) In order to know exactly where to hang your brackets and rod, first attach the drapes to the rod and hold the rod up to see what height it needs to be hung at to ensure that the drapes just reach the floor.  If you try to decide on the rod location/height without actually holding up the fully attached drapes, you likely won’t get the right height because it’s hard to accurately measure how far the top of the drapes will be from the rod when hung.  Make sense? 

Tip 4). Make sure to hang the rod/ rod brackets several inches wider and higher than the window itself.  This makes the window appear larger and allows you to take advantage of the most possible light when the drapes are open.  The inside edge of the drapes should just barely cover the outside edge of the window when the drapes are fully open.  My living room window is 12 feet wide and I hung the outside rod brackets 24” wider on both sides of the window.  So long as you have the appropriate width of panels, the wider the window, the further out your outside rod brackets will need to be. 

Please let me know if these tips are helpful!

I know what you’re thinking—45’s never looked so good! 🔥😜 I’m not the kind of person to be shy about my birthday.  I make sure everyone knows (I just had to remind Skip and it didn’t disappoint me one bit)! I get exactly what I want every year—I spend time with friends and my family,, go out to eat, and eat peppermint ice cream while watching While You Were Sleeping. 
But you guys—every year on this day, I really do feel sooo grateful to be alive—and to get to experience all the things that come along in this life.  And guess what?  Good news for you young folk—life just gets better with age.  These years in my 40’s have truly been the best years of my life so far!  I enjoy my kids tremendously, Brian and I are finally figuring some things out and reaping the rewards of 23 years of hard work, I can wear pimple patches all over my face and not give a dang, and I can dance—even when people are watching. 😊
Here is my festival tree!  I hope you like it!

I spent about three hours this morning desperately trying to find a way to get Camp (who is serving a mission in Brazil) a Christmas package.  Even though  I wouldn’t change our circumstances,  I will still miss him terribly this Christmas.  Thinking about him, though, made me reflect again on HOW LUCKY I am to be surrounded by people I love at Christmas.  I cannot imagine anything worse than being alone for Christmas.  If YOU are going to be alone for Christmas and you live anywhere close to me, I invite you to join our family.  I promise to give you a special meal, lights, music and good company. ❤️❤️

Christmas in the kitchen.  I hate spending money on new appliances, (especially at Christmas time! 😩) but when your sister spends 3 hours making the MOST delicious stuffing ever for Thanksgiving and almost loses it when the oven rack it’s on falls…you know it’s time. 😣. So here she is!  Also, I’ve had several people ask me why we decided to go back to electric after having had a gas range for 8 years.  Well, the whole reason we got gas last time was because people told me how much faster it looks.  And for me, that was just not the case.  Our propane LG oven cooked soooooo slow.  AND, it seemed like it just never heated up all the way.  For example, in all the years we had it, I was not ever able to brown chicken on the stove top.  Crazy, right?! And to be fair, I don’t know if the problem was with it being propane verses natural gas, or if our LG oven was just a lemon.  I may never know…  regardless, now I’ve got an electric cooktop (just regular radiant heat, not induction) and it still cooks waaaay faster than my propane LG one ever did.

One one hand, I don’t usually decorate for Christmas with Legos…and it kinda looks like clutter.  But on the other hand, my boy built it.  And it’s his contribution to my Christmas decor.  And someday he won’t be here to contribute.  And so I keep it there and love it.

Earlier tonight, just Skip and I were at home.  I had been cleaning, and he had been watching TV upstairs.  After a while, I called to him to come downstairs to go on a walk with me.  He grumbled a bit, but before long, the two of us walked out into the chilly December night.  The streets were dark, except for the Christmas lights on the occasional houses.  I admired the lights and Skip told me he especially likes the icicle kind.  We  continued talking and every 1/4 mile or so, we’d sprint for a short distance as we counted to 10.  But each time we started walking again, Skip would hold my hand.  And while we walked, and talked, and admired the lights, and held hands…I knew this would be a night I would cherish forever.. ❤️❤️❤️
#christmastraditions #christmastradition #christmaspuzzle #christmasmantel

I do count down the days until Christmas, but it’s not actually because I’m so excited for THAT day.  Rather, it’s because I’m counting the days I have LEFT before my favorite season of the year… is over.  For me, it really is the most wonderful time of the year.

I wonder if people really do use their “wrapping stations”? This is mine.  Also, yes—that is the same tree that you saw in the picture of my entry.  It actually belongs in Skip’s room, but I’ve been moving it around for all my pictures. Ha!

A few weeks ago when I was digging out the Christmas stuff, I came across this bear (see it on the chair? Swipe to see it better.) I got it almost 22 years ago when Brian and I were celebrating our first anniversary down on the Las Vegas Strip.  It had been the hardest year of my life BY FAR, and the hardest year for Brian as well.  There had been many times in that year when I had sat sobbing, wondering if our marriage would even last that first year.  And so on that night, when we picked out our bears, I named mine “Wish” to be a secret reminder of the wish I made that night.  The wish I made wasn’t one that could be granted in an instant. Rather, it is one that would take lots of time and lots of effort.  But almost 22 years later, I am so grateful to say that my wish has come true—or rather, that it continues to BECOME true… little by little, year after year.
Well, I got most of the house clean, but there were lots of things I didn’t have time or energy to get to.  You’ll see.  I hope you still enjoy seeing our downstairs at Christmas time. ❤️❤️

As i look back on this month that has flown by so quickly, I realize I took on too much.  I packed my days too full to be able to really feel the calm and peace of the season.  I hope to feel that today and tomorrow and for the rest of this month.  And next year, I will try to choose differently.

(Written on Sunday, December 10, 2023)

Dear Family and Friends, 

Oh, how I appreciate and have needed this day of rest…or at least this day of Christmas-letter writing. 

A couple weeks ago, we all spent 14 hours at one of the girls’ wrestling meets.  Skip went to the meet with no money, and I’ll tell you what—nothing is harder for Skip than to be at a place with a concession stand (the boy loves junk food) with no money to spend there.  Around lunch time, we left the meet briefly to get some lunch, and then Skip ran off again and we didn’t see much of him.  After awhile, I was surprised that he never came back asking  for more food.  Well, at the end of the night, we found out he and his buddy had devised a Barter Kings-style trading scheme that began with a penny, which they then traded for some pens, which they then sold for a dollar each.  They had continued this trading scheme long enough that by the end of the day, they had made enough money to purchase three bags of snack-sized chips, two servings of biscuits with gravy, one small plate of nachos and two hotdogs. Oh, for the love…

And speaking of Skip, I’ve been waiting for him to transition into the world of caring about girls,  but instead of it happening as a transition, it happened as a thief in the night—or rather, in the day; Tuesday to be exact.  He was at another wrestling meet when a girl delivered to him a “brrrr basket.” (I’ve come to understand that a brrr basket is December’s version of a valentine.) And he hasn’t been the same since.  So it begins for our last and final baby.  Deep breath in…..long exhale out. 

Earlier this year, when Danin was playing volleyball and Jane was running cross country, Brian and I were always trying to juggle their different races and games, which often conflicted.  One of Jane’s races fell on the day of Danin’s last game of the season.  Because it was her last game, Brian and I had planned to attend it instead of Jane’s race.  However, that morning, Jane texted us to let us know how much she had hoped we could be at her race. (Continued in comments)
Until next year.  Goodbye, Christmas. 😭

Okay so here are the specifics—
1) When I say no spending money on myself, I’m talking about things that are WANTS rather than needs.  However, I will continue to buy makeup ( I don’t wear a lot) and get my hair done quarterly.  And I desperately need a new bra, so I’ll probably get one of those, too. 
2) This doesn’t include food.  I will still buy ice  cream and go out to eat occasionally.  Those things are about relationships and relationships are important. 
3.) “Old money”  will be the only money I can spend. “Old money” is defined (by me) as money that I make ONLY by selling stuff I already have. 
4). Gifts don’t count.  So I will likely get something for my anniversary, birthday and Christmas from Brian that I will have picked out. 
This means that for 12 months (with the exception of those three special occasions I just mentioned) I will not buy any clothes, shoes, accessories, home decor, plants, or other Homegoods. 😬😬

With the money we save by my not buying these things for a year, I’m hoping to at some point have enough money to buy 8 new kitchen chairs.  I’d also love to start putting money aside to eventually buy a piece of land on which to build another home.  These are big goals for me.  And they will require sacrifices—sacrifices that I am finally willing to make.  Wish me luck!

During the time we had our oven, I talked to numerous appliance technicians who all told me the same two things—1) Never use the self cleaning function on your oven as it can cause so many problems (your oven expanding so the racks fall is just one of many!) and 2) For KITCHEN appliances specifically, always go with American made.  Have you gotten this advice, too??
